HEADWORD: Naumachy
<hw>Nau"ma*chy</hw> <pr>(n⟦add⟧"m⟦adot⟧*k⟦ycr⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>naumachia</ets>, Gr. <grk>naymachi`a</grk>;
<grk>nay^s</grk> ship + <grk>ma`chh</grk> fight, battle,
<grk>ma`chesqai</grk> to fight.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A naval battle;
esp., a mock sea fight put on by the ancient Romans.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Rom. Antiq.)</fld> <def>A show or spectacle
representing a sea fight; also, a place for such exhibitions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nauplius</ent>⟦br⟧
